6","1038":"1038","1135":"1135","1069":"1069","1100":"1100","1133":"1133","1034":"1034","Alnwick, Northumberland, England":"Alnwick, Northumberland, England","Jerusalem, Jerusalem, Israel":"Jerusalem, Jerusalem, Israël","Semar, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Whitby, Yorkshire, England":"Whitby, Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"about 1071–1133":"about 1071–1133","1069–1135":"1069–1135","1069–Male":"1069–Deceased","1071–1133":"1071–1133","1073–1150":"1073–1150","1075–Male":"1075–Deceased","1082–1180":"1082–1180","1075–Female":"1075–Deceased","1088–Male":"1088–Deceased","1034–1096":"1034–1096","1038–1100":"1038–1100","about 1071":"about 1071","1088":"1088","1066":"1066","1086":"1086","1075":"1075","1096":"1096","1150":"1150","1073":"1073","1082":"1082","1071":"1071","1180":"1180","1106":"1106","1038":"1038","1135":"1135","1069":"1069","1100":"1100","1133":"1133","1034":"1034","Alnwick, Northumberland, England":"Alnwick, Northumberland, England","Jerusalem, Jerusalem, Israel":"Jerusalem, Jerusalem, Israel","Semar, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Whitby, Yorkshire, England":"Whitby, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Percy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin):","nickname from Old French <i>percehaie</i> ‘pierce hedge’ (Old French <i>percer</i> ‘to pierce, penetrate’ + <i>haie</i> ‘hedge, fence’), perhaps with the sense of someone breaking into an enclosure. <i>Percehaie</i> is the name of one of the sons of the foxes Renart and Hermeline in the medieval French epic <i>Roman de Renart</i>, whose earliest known version is from the 1170s. The surname is older than that, but it may originate in a nickname for the fox as ‘enclosure piercer’, perhaps amounting to ‘chicken thief’.","habitational name from any of several places called Percy in Calvados, Eure, and Manche; William <i>de Perci</i>, the Domesday tenant-in-chief and under-tenant of Hugh, Earl of Chester, came from either Percy-en-Auge (Eure) or Percy (Manche)."],"variants":[{"name":"Piercey","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Percy  ."]},{"name":"Piercy","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Percy  ."]},{"name":"Pearcey","meanings":["English: variant of   Percy  ."]},{"name":"Peercy","meanings":["English: variant of   Percy  ."]},{"name":"Pearcy","meanings":["English: variant of   Percy  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705183,"age":15,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705184,"age":25,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":35,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Percy Jr was born about 1071, in Whitby, Yorkshire, England, his father, Sir William de Percy Sr, was 39 and his mother, Emma de Port, was 34. He had at least 1 son with Mrs William de Perry. He died in 1133, at the age of 63."},"et":{"about 1071–1133":"umbes 1071–1133","1069–1135":"1069–1135","1069–Male":"1069–Surnud","1071–1133":"1071–1133","1073–1150":"1073–1150","1075–Male":"1075–Surnud","1082–1180":"1082–1180","1075–Female":"1075–Surnud","1088–Male":"1088–Surnud","1034–1096":"1034–1096","1038–1100":"1038–1100","about 1071":"umbes 1071","1088":"1088","1066":"1066","1086":"1086","1075":"1075","1096":"1096","1150":"1150","1073":"1073","1082":"1082","1071":"1071","1180":"1180","1106":"1106","1038":"1038","1135":"1135","1069":"1069","1100":"1100","1133":"1133","1034":"1034","Alnwick, Northumberland, England":"Alnwick, Northumberland, England","Jerusalem, Jerusalem, Israel":"Jerusalem, Jerusalem, Iisrael","Se